Data structures are ways of organizing and storing data so that it can be accessed and modified efficiently. There isn’t a single “complete” list (since new or hybrid structures can be created), but here’s a broad and commonly accepted classification:

1. Primitive Data Structures

These are basic, built-in types:

Integer
Float (real numbers)
Character
Boolean
Pointer (in low-level languages)
2. Non-Primitive Data Structures
A. Linear Data Structures

Elements are arranged sequentially.

Array – fixed-size, indexed collection
Linked List
