4. File/Data Storage Structures (High-level)
Files
Databases (Relational, NoSQL structures)

Data Structure: A way of organizing, storing, and managing data in memory so that it can be accessed and modified efficiently.

Primitive Data Structure: A basic built-in data type that stores a single value (e.g., int, char, float, boolean).
Non-Primitive Data Structure: A data structure that stores and organizes multiple values using primitive data types (e.g., array, linked list, stack, queue, tree).
Abstract Data Type (ADT): A logical model that defines what operations can be performed on data without specifying how they are implemented (e.g., stack, queue, list, set).


Primitive Data Types (Single-Line Definitions)
Integer (int): Stores whole numbers without decimal points.
Float (float): Stores numbers with decimal points.
Double (double): Stores decimal numbers with higher precision than float.
Character (char): Stores a single character such as a letter, digit, or symbol.
Boolean (bool): Stores one of two values: true or false.
Pointer: Stores the memory address of another variable.
Byte: Stores a small integer value, typically 8 bits in size.
Short: Stores an integer value using less memory than a standard integer.
Long: Stores larger integer values than a standard integer.

Simple one-line summary:
Primitive data types are the basic built-in types used to store single values directly in memory.


The size of primitive data types depends on the programming language and system architecture. For most interview and academic purposes (especially C/C++), you can use the following:

