Time Complexity – Complete Notes (DSA Basics)
1. What is Time Complexity?

Time complexity measures how the running time of an algorithm grows as the input size increases.

It does not measure exact execution time in seconds. Instead, it describes the algorithm’s growth trend.

Definition

Time Complexity: The amount of time an algorithm takes to complete as a function of input size n.

2. Why is Time Complexity Important?

Time complexity helps us:

Compare algorithms efficiently

Predict performance for large inputs

Choose the best solution in coding interviews and real-world applications

3. Big O Notation (Most Important)

Big O notation represents the worst-case time complexity of an algorithm.
# Time Complexity Cheat Sheet

A quick overview of common time complexities and their performance.

| Complexity | Name         | Performance Description |
|------------|--------------|--------------------------|
| O(1)       | Constant     | Excellent               |
| O(log n)   | Logarithmic  | Very Fast               |
| O(n)       | Linear       | Good                    |
| O(n log n) | Linearithmic | Efficient               |
| O(n²)      | Quadratic    | Slow for large inputs   |
| O(n³)      | Cubic        | Very Slow               |
| O(2ⁿ)      | Exponential  | Extremely Slow          |
| O(n!)      | Factorial    | Worst (Not practical)   |
4. Understanding Each Complexity
O(1) – Constant Time

Execution time does not depend on input size.

Example (Java)
O(log n) – Logarithmic Time

Input size is reduced by half in each step.

Example

Binary Search

Operations in balanced trees (BST, AVL, Red-Black)

O(n) – Linear Time

Execution time grows proportionally with input size.

Example
O(n log n) – Linearithmic Time

Efficient sorting algorithms usually have this complexity.

Examples

Merge Sort

Quick Sort (average case)

Heap Sort

O(n²) – Quadratic Time

Nested loops over the same input.

Example
O(2ⁿ) – Exponential Time

Each step branches into two possibilities.

Example

Recursive Fibonacci without optimization

O(n!) – Factorial Time

All permutations are generated.

Example

Traveling Salesman brute force

Generating all permutations

5. Best, Average, and Worst Case

# Time Complexity Cases

## Types of Cases in Time Complexity

| Case         | Meaning                                  |
|--------------|-------------------------------------------|
| Best Case    | Minimum time an algorithm can take        |
| Average Case | Expected time for typical inputs          |
| Worst Case   | Maximum time an algorithm can take        |

Example: Linear Search

Best Case: Element found at first position → O(1)

Average Case: Element found in middle → O(n)

Worst Case: Element found at last position or not present → O(n)

# 6. Important Time Complexity Rules

## Rule 1: Ignore Constants
O(2n) = O(n)

Constants do not matter for large inputs.

---

## Rule 2: Keep the Dominant Term
O(n² + n + 1) = O(n²)

The highest-growth term dominates.

---

## Rule 3: Nested Loops Multiply
If one loop runs inside another:

O(n) × O(n) = O(n²)

---

## Rule 4: Consecutive Loops Add
O(n) + O(n) = O(n)

The larger complexity dominates.

---

# 7. Space Complexity (Also Important)

Space complexity measures the extra memory used by an algorithm.

## Examples

- **O(1)** → Uses fixed extra memory  
- **O(n)** → Uses memory proportional to input size  
- **O(log n)** → Recursion stack in balanced recursive algorithms  

---

