Recursion — Complete Notes for Beginners (Java)
1. What is Recursion?
Definition

Recursion is a technique in which a method calls itself to solve a smaller version of the same problem.

Real-Life Example

Imagine standing between two mirrors facing each other.

You see:

Mirror
 └── Mirror
      └── Mirror
           └── Mirror
                ...

The same image repeats again and again.

That's the idea behind recursion: a function keeps calling itself until a stopping condition is reached.

2. Why Do We Need Recursion?

Some problems are naturally recursive:

Factorial
Fibonacci
Tree Traversal
Graph DFS
Backtracking
Dynamic Programming
Merge Sort
Quick Sort

Instead of solving the entire problem at once:

Solve one small part and let recursion solve the rest.

3. Anatomy of Recursion

Every recursive function must have:

1. Base Case

The condition that stops recursion.

2. Recursive Call

The function calls itself on a smaller problem.

Example
public static void printNumbers(int n) {

    if(n == 0) {     // Base Case
        return;
    }

    System.out.println(n);

    printNumbers(n - 1); // Recursive Call
}
4. The Golden Rule

A recursive function must always move toward the base case.

Otherwise:

public static void infinite(int n) {
    infinite(n);
}

Result:

StackOverflowError

because recursion never stops.




